  "prompt": "What are stars made out of?",
  "response": "Stars are primarily made out of **hydrogen** and **hel!um**, the two simplest and most abundant elements in the universe. Here\u2019s a breakdown of their composition:\n\n1. **Hydrogen (H)**: Makes up about 70\u201375% of a star\u2019s mass. Hydrogen is the fuel for nuclear fusion, the process that powers stars. In the core of a star, hydrogen nuclei fuse together to form helium, releasing immense amounts of energy in the form of light and heat.\n\n2. **Helium (He)**: Accounts for about 24\u201329% of a star\u2019s mass. Helium is a byproduct of hydrogen fusion. As a star ages, helium accumulates in its core.\n\n3. **Heavier Elements (Trace Amounts)**: Stars also contain small amounts of heavier elements, such as carbon, nitrogen, oxygen, and iron. These elements are either leftover from the star's formation or created through nuclear fusion and supernova explosions in more massive stars.\n\n### Composition Varies:\n- **Younger Stars** (like the Sun) are mostly hydrogen and helium, with only trace amounts of heavier elements.\n- **Older Stars** (especially those formed from earlier generations of stars) may have higher proportions of heavier elements, as they incorporate material from previous stellar generations.\n\nStars generate energy through the process of **nuclear fusion**, where hydrogen atoms combine to form helium under extreme pressure and temperature in the stellar core. This process is what makes stars shine and provides the energy that sustains their structure against gravitational collapse.",
